[normal]2. Our perspective on the extractive industries[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal]  The extraction of
[normal] 
[normal]minerals is
[normal] the cornerstone of all industrial activities
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]it 
[normal]underpin
[normal]s
[normal] the global economy. Without the commodities produced by mining and energy companies the world would not be housed, clothed, fed or transported. 
[normal]Without the extractive industries, t
[normal]here would be no globalisation and sophisticated modern economies, such as 
[normal]the UK, which depend on the supply and trade in commodities
[normal],
[normal] would be unable to function.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2  The extractive sector is not merely a collection of mines and oil fields
[normal]. It is instead a complex global industry that connects resources with customers through
[normal] a network of transport, supply and logistics. At the heart of the extractive sector is the commodity market which efficiently ensures that consumers worldwide have access to the resources they need, when they need them and at competitive prices.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3   
[normal]Mining is becoming more valuable. According to statistics from the International Council
[normal] on Mining and Met
[normal]als
[normal], the value of global production of metals rose from $214 billion in 2000 to $854 billion in 2011. More importantly, the value of the world’s metal
[normal] output ha
[normal]s been rising at a faster
[normal] rate than the overall increase in global GDP, a consequence of greater demand for metals in the emerging markets. Simply put, mining’s contribution to the global economy is becoming more significant. It is generating mor
[normal]e wealth for producing countries and for those countries, such as the UK, which support 
[normal]the global trade in commodities with finance, marketing and technical skills.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4  We believe that sustainability
[normal] must be central
[normal] to the operations of extractive companies, not least because the source of many vital minerals is now mainly to be found in the developing world. Due to the nature
[normal] of
[normal] the
[normal] business, extractive companies must acknowledge the significant impact of their oper
[normal]ations on the environment and local communities. At the 
[normal]same time, extractive companies
[normal] have a distinct opportunity to render assistance to communities and governments in poorer countries.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Mining com
[normal]panies, such as Glencore
[normal],
[normal] have
[normal] exceptional skills in pro
[normal]ject management as well as access to knowhow and resources. 
[normal]The best operators in
[normal] the extractive sector are aware
[normal] tha
[normal]t their licence to operate 
[normal]depend
[normal]s
[normal] on their good relations with local communities as well as national governments.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5  At Glencore
[normal] w
[normal]e constantly strive to find new ways to improve how we manage our health, safety and environmental practices, the welfare of all our workers and our support for the development and well-being of the communities in which we 
[normal]operate
[normal].  We are open and transpa
[normal]rent in our engagement with our stakeholders. Respect for human rights is fundamental to all our activities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]6
[normal] 
[normal] Glencore
[normal] plays a unique role in the extractive sector bringing together mining assets, refining, transportation
[normal], logistics and marketing. 
[normal]Arguably 
[normal]n
[normal]o other company in the extractive sector has
[normal] the breadth of expertise and skills in extractive technologies
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]commodity trading and transportation/logistics.
