[normal]3.10[bold] [bold]What is the competitive landscape for the extractive[bold] industries in the 21st Century [bold]and is it in the UK’s interest to [bold]remain a global centre for them?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]During the first decade of this century, the mining and
[normal] extractive sector
[normal]s
[normal] enjoyed a period of high commodity prices and heavy investment. Recent trends in metal
[normal]s
[normal] and 
[normal]in 
[normal]mineral
[normal]s
[normal] suggest that a period of consolidation and adjustment may 
[normal]now 
[normal]be underway. This should lead to a more competitive environment for extractive companie
[normal]s, one in which th
[normal]e more
[normal] efficient players will
[normal] thrive
[normal] while those that are less resilient may fall by the
[normal] wayside
[normal]. In such an environment, successful companie
[normal]s seeking capital and skills will gravitate towards the most efficient and liquid markets in both financial and human resources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK has a big endowment of skills in natural r
[normal]esources, in part becaus
[normal]e of offshore
[normal] oil and gas production
[normal] in the North Sea but also because of Britain’s
[normal] colonial legacy
[normal] and a long and distinguished history of commodity trading, based in the City of London. T
[normal]he continued presence of a number of large extractive 
[normal]companies, li
[normal]sted on the Lo
[normal]ndon Stock Exchange, is also important. While the value of oil and gas production 
[normal]in the UK 
[normal]can be quantified, it is difficul
[normal]t to measure the benefit to Britain
[normal] 
[normal]of extractive companies established in Britain but whose activities are mainly overseas. However, it would be a mistake to focus only on dividends repatriated or tax paid 
[normal](although as noted above, these are themselves significant benefits)
[normal]. 
[normal]The UK derives 
[normal]huge benefit 
[normal]from mining and oil companie
[normal]s 
[normal]in 
[normal]terms of training and 
[normal]the 
[normal]employment of Britons in posts overseas and in the services activity generated in Britain by the corporate activities of extractive companies
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Moreover, the corporate presence and 
[normal]stock exchange listing of extractive companies, including many of the world’s largest enterprises, represents an important attraction to foreign capital, thus boosting the UK’s position as a global financial centre.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the future
[normal],
[normal] the extractive sector wi
[normal]ll
[normal] continue to see the UK as a natural corporate home if it retains its competitive advantage in terms of finance, skills
[normal], regulation, tax
[normal] and its open-
[normal]door policy to foreign investors.  As
[normal] the physical output of 
[normal]minerals in the UK dwindles, the UK’s impor
[normal]tance as a home to the extractive sector will depend more on its ability to provide high-level skills in finance
[normal], trading
[normal] and project management and engi
[normal]neering.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The opportunity exists for Britain to enhance its position as a global hub for energy, mining
[normal] and resources with further economic benefit to the UK. In seizing that opportunity, the UK must commit to
[normal] remain
[normal]ing
[normal] an open 
[normal]and efficient 
[normal]marketplace for the conduct of 
[normal]commodity trading, corporate finance and 
[normal]business
[normal], generally
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]